Bombarding in the name of morality?
NEW YORK – Eloquence has always been one of the key strengths of American President Barack Obama.
It seems however today that his words have cornered him into a trap.
After saying in March that the United States "would not tolerate the use of chemical weapons against the Syrian people" and mentioning last year a "red line" that was not supposed to be crossed, Obama will lose face if he does not react energetically to the massacre, attributed to the Syrian regime, of more than 1,000 civilians using sarin gas.
Obviously, the risk of losing face is not a valid reason to attack another country.
But why did Obama get stuck with such rhetoric in the first place.
What's so special about this particular line?
The US Secretary of State John Kerry is right to qualify the use of gas as a "moral obscenity".
But torturing children, who were the seeds of civil war two years ago, is no less so.
Is it morally more obscene to kill civilians with chemicals, to bomb them, shoot at them, or starve them to death?
It is commonly accepted, since the use of mustard gas during World War I, that some weapons are more immoral than others.
Massive destructive weapons, nuclear bombs in particular, certainly cause more damage and more quickly than conventional weapons.
But is there really a clear moral distinction between killing about 100,000 people with a single atomic bomb in Hiroshima and killing even more people in a single night in Tokyo with incendiary bombs?
Was it more immoral to gaze at the Jews than to shoot them in mass graves ?
A view, defended notably by Nicholas Kristof of the New York Times, is that swift punitive action could convince Syrian President Bashar al-Assad to give up using chemical weapons and return to "more mundane means of massacring his people".
In my opinion, that makes no sense.
The question is surely that of the massacre, not the methods used.
In any case, moral indignation, however justified it may be, is not a sufficient reason to go to war.
Mao Zedong was responsible for the deaths of more than 40 million Chinese in the 1950s and 1960s.
No sane person has suggested that a military intervention in China was a good idea.
In the 1980s, Saddam Hussein gassed hundreds of thousands of Iranians and Kurds – with the support of the United States.
Is it then a legal question? The use of chemical weapons constitutes, in fact, a violation of international conventions, including the Convention on the Prohibition of Chemical Weapons, which Syria never signed and the Geneva Protocol, to which it is a party.
Therefore, there are valid reasons to consider Assad as a war criminal, in which case he must be indicted by the International Criminal Court (ICC), which was, incidentally, established by a treaty that the United States never ratified.
But bypassing the United Nations and launching an illegal war to punish an illegal act is not an easily defensible policy.
However, one could argue that the "international community", or Western countries, or the United States as the principal Western power, must certainly draw a line somewhere.
How can responsible governments simply turn a blind eye when innocent people are being massacred en masse?
Tolerating a genocide is not acceptable.
But where exactly must one draw a line?
How many murders constitute a genocide ?
Thousands?
Hundreds of thousands ?
Millions of them?
Or, does the number not count for anything?
A genocide is ultimately a matter of intent, there is a will to kill or persecute individuals because of their race, ethnic affiliation or belief.
In principle, killing ten people for these reasons – or even two – would constitute a form of genocide.
The problem can be approached from a different angle.
The question to ask before intervening militarily in a country is whether this action has a chance to improve the situation, save lives, and make the world a safer place.
Yes, violence against civilians, whether through sarin gas or combat helicopters, is a moral obscenity.
To respond to this implies asking oneself : what is the best solution ?
Justice and morality have little to do with a decision like that.
Like the action of the ICC, "humanitarian intervention" has a greater chance of producing results in a weak country (for example, Serbia, Mali, or Sierra Leone) than in the case of a great power.
No one would contemplate missile strikes on China or Russia in the name of defending human rights or enforcing international norms and conventions related to war.
Syria, as many have noted, is not Libya or Mali.
She is not a great power either.
But the civil war raging there has already spilled over its borders, involving more important countries, including Iran, Turkey, and Russia.
It is beyond doubt that a regional conflagration would be infinitely worse than the moral obscenities of a civil war.
It's not absolutely certain that U.S. intervention would reduce the risk of a wider conflict.
In fact, some proponents of US intervention – both neoconservatives and "liberal hawks" – seem to want the opposite: they call for a war with Iran.
And Obama probably established a link in his mind between the red line over Syria and the one he drew for Iran, perhaps just as reflexively, to prevent it from developing nuclear arms.
What, then, are we to expect from US strikes on Syrian targets, when Obama has already stated that they are not intended to bring down the Syrian regime ?
They will not bring an end to the civil war.
But a single missile will be enough to make the United States a direct participant in this war, provoking a resurgence of violence.
Taking that risk to save Obama's honor doesn't seem particularly wise.
This view is shared by many Syrians, including among the rebels.
It's the opinion of most Europeans.
And by a majority of Americans.
It may even be Obama's own view, which is why he is desperately trying to buy time, by delegating to the US Congress the authority to use military force in Syria.
Since taking office, his relations with Congress have been far from easy.
But he needs it more than ever today to cover his back.
